
雪とけて　村一ぱいの　子どもかな
As the snow melts,
the town is flooded
with children.
— Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

(primrose)
咲きみちて　庭盛り上がる　桜草
In full blossom,
the garden rejoices – 
Primrose.
— Seison Yamaguchi (1892-1988)

(playing by the river)
夏川を　こすうれしさよ　手にぞうり
Summer, river crossing;
such joy, sandals in hand.
— Yosa Buson (1716-1783)

(horseback milky way)
朝だちや　馬のかしらの　あまの川
Morning Departure
Horseback
Milky Way
— Meisetsu Naitou (1847-1926)

(birds in a bush)
夕立や　草葉をつかむ　むら雀
Evening showers
call sparrows to
this bramble shanty town.
— Yosa Buson (1716-1783)

(picture of a fly begging)
やれ打つな　はえが手をする　足をする
Stop, don’t swat!
Can’t you see the fly
begging for mercy?
— Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

秋の夜や旅の男の針仕事
An autumn evening;
a travelling man's 
needlework.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

食べてゐる牛の口より蓼の花
Hanging from the mouth
of a grazing cow:
a knotweed flower.
-- Takano Sujuu (1893-1976)

露の玉百千万も葎かな
Beads of dew,
a multitude of them
resting upon the foliage.
-- Kawabata Bousha (1897-1941)

汲みあてて朝寒ひびく釣瓶かな
The clanging of the bucket
rings out into the cold morning air
as I draw it up for water.
-- Hisajo Sugita (1890-1946)

朝ばかり日のとどく渓のむくげ哉
The first morning light
reaches a valley of
blossoming Rose of Sharon.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

手にとらば消んなみだぞ あつき秋の霜
If I could gather them in my hands,
these inexorable tears:
a searing early frost.
– Matsuo Bashō (1644-1694)

手の前に蝶の息つぐ茸哉
Taking a break,
a butterfly rests 
on a nearby mushroom.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

どの星の下が我家ぞ秋の風
Anywhere beneath the stars
will be my home:
Autumn Winds.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

くやしくも熟柿仲間の座につきぬ
Disappointment:
unable to join
a clique of ripe persimmons.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

母親を霜よけにして寝た子哉
With mother
as a shield from the frost
the child sleeps.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

猫の子のくるくる舞やちる木のは
A kitten performs
its twirly and tumbling dance
among the falling leaves.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

夜の雪だまつて通る人もあり
It is snowing tonight, and people 
silently 
walk by.
– Kobayashi Issa (1763-1828)

つくづくと雪山近く歩きけり
I walked beneath
the snowy mountains
in awe.
– Hoshino Tatsuko (1903-1984)
